162. Find Peak Element
Problem

A peak element is an element that is strictly greater than its neighbors.

Given an integer array nums, return the index of any peak element.

The array may contain multiple peaks. Returning the index of any one of them is acceptable.

Note
nums[-1] = -∞
nums[n]  = -∞

Elements outside the array are considered negative infinity.

Example 1
nums = [1,2,3,1]

Output = 2

Explanation:

1 2 3 1
    ↑
3 > 2
3 > 1

Therefore, 3 is a peak element.

Example 2
nums = [1,2,1,3,5,6,4]

Output = 5

Explanation:

1 2 1 3 5 6 4
          ↑
6 > 5
6 > 4

Peak element found at index 5.

Another valid peak:

1 2 1 3 5 6 4
  ↑
2 > 1
2 > 1

Peak at index 1.

Either answer is accepted.

Peak Element ≠ Maximum Element

A peak is simply a local maximum.

Example:

[1,5,2,10,1]

Peaks:

1 5 2 10 1
  ↑   ↑
5 is a peak
10 is a peak

The problem asks for any peak, not necessarily the largest element.

Why Binary Search Works

The key observation is:

If we compare:

nums[mid]

with:

nums[mid + 1]

we can determine which side must contain a peak.

Case 1: Uphill Slope
1 2 3 4 5
    ↑ ↑
   mid

Suppose:

nums[mid] < nums[mid + 1]

Example:

2 < 3

We are moving uphill.

↗

A peak must exist on the right side.

Move:

low = mid + 1;
Case 2: Downhill Slope
5 4 3 2 1
↑ ↑
mid

Suppose:

nums[mid] > nums[mid + 1]

Example:

5 > 4

We are moving downhill.

↘

A peak must exist on the left side (including mid).

Move:

high = mid;
Main Idea
If
nums[mid] < nums[mid + 1]

Peak lies on the right side.

low = mid + 1;
Else
nums[mid] > nums[mid + 1]

Peak lies on the left side (including mid).

high = mid;
Code
class Solution {

    public int findPeakElement(int[] nums) {

        int low = 0;
        int high = nums.length - 1;

        while(low < high) {

            int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

            if(nums[mid] < nums[mid + 1]) {
                low = mid + 1;
            }
            else {
                high = mid;
            }
        }

        return low;
    }
}
