Why Does a Peak Always Exist?

Because:

nums[-1] = -∞
nums[n]  = -∞

At the boundaries, the array starts from negative infinity and ends at negative infinity.

Therefore, there must always be at least one local maximum (peak).

Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity

Each iteration removes half of the search space.

n → n/2 → n/4 → n/8 ...

Therefore:

O(log n)
Space Complexity

Only a few variables are used.

O(1)
Pattern Recognition

Use this Binary Search pattern when:

Need to find a peak/local maximum.
Comparing adjacent elements helps determine the search direction.
Problem requires O(log n).
Key Takeaway

The entire solution is based on one observation:

if(nums[mid] < nums[mid + 1])

👉 We are moving uphill, so a peak exists on the right.

low = mid + 1;

Otherwise:

high = mid;

👉 We are moving downhill, so a peak exists on the left (including mid).

When:

low == high

that index represents a peak element.
